segments.text: I have a lot of stuff to be found out.
Our problems run from adoption of babies and alcoholism all the way through the alphabet, clear down the wheelchairs and things of that sort.
Are most of your problems with the blacks?
No.
Blacks have Latin.
I would say that approximately 60% were blacks, another 20% or so were Anglos, and another 20% were Lesbians.
Anglos.
Where do you get most of your volunteers from?
Housewives and retirees.
Are the retirees good volunteers?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, it's just remarkable.
There's a man out here, he had a house that you could set this in his backyard.
And two stories.
And he must be, must have all the money that he's ever going to use and some more beside.
and yet he is one of the best roadrunners we got.

Call him up and he's out just out today on a little side street called Military Street up here in North Bryan taking a woman to a doctor and uh it runs all all the way from uh of course in people it it there's practically no no no stratification there they're all
all retirees and whether they're just on call.
One case that I thought was quite interesting was a boy who was graduating from Allen School.
And he had a football scholarship to one of the colleges.
And his mother was working.
But she'd had an automobile accident.
And she had fallen behind on his tuition.
And he had to have his grades by a certain date to get his scholarship.
And they would not release his grades until his tuition had been paid.
And she had no car even to make a loan.
And so she came to Bible what to do and how to do.
And it was a case of talking to her employer a little bit.
Yeah, he said, why didn't you come to me?
He said, of course, I'll let her have the money and she could work it out out of her salary.
So that was solved.
But this Junior Museum, I'm treasurer of it.

manage have a great many duties in connection with keeping it going like hammer and saw and and the screwdriver and things of that sort and I'm very fond of it because I think that we do instill into these kids some little bit of scientific knowledge and respect for their environment and respect for nature and I'm sure that in some cases
We have pointed some of them to A&M, and they've gone, of course, plus their high school and all the other things they acquired.
But we have helped them in ways, in their thinking, orient, and I'm hopeful or feel quite sure that sooner or later we'll have fed into A&M quite a number of the kids.
with the museum with the youngsters way back before he had to go to the hospital because he got some cards from the little boys that he had helped them solve a problem of moving materials.
I took a bunch of 10 kids, limited to 10,

I wanted to be anywhere from 9 to 11 but I had one boy about 12 or 12 and a half and we had a chunk of concrete out of a road but about as big as a fourth of this floor area, one chunk of concrete and the kids learned something about levers, block and tackle and ropes and hitches and
We just moved that thing all over the area.
We got it up on skids first, then we put rollers under it, we moved it around, and we determined its weight by calculation.
I had another chunk of the same, broken off the same piece, so I determined its density.
And having found the area and the thickness of the chunk, it had its volume.
But if you have the volume and the density, you have the weight.
So we calculated the weight of it, 1,970 pounds.
We got that up on skids and rollers.
That's a really marvelous practical experience.
You can look at it in a textbook and it just doesn't quite... Yeah, and those kids had fun because we used two-by-sixes as levers, you know.
And they'd get an end of that under there and first thing, they didn't have enough support under the fulcrum.
So they learned something about that.
Then they got too short a bite and they broke the two-for-six off.
So they learned an awful lot of things about that.
And then I took it up on a hill intentionally so that a couple of them could move it on rollers just by pulling on it.
Up that hill, they couldn't begin to take it up that hill, so I got the block and tackled.
And I had equivalent to 11 lines up.
11, that's quite a lot of power, 11 times what you're pulling.
And, uh...
He went over to the hardware store and borrowed some gear.
Oh, I got bummed.
I needed to know how much we were pulling.
So I got one of these scales they used for weighing bales of cotton, you know, about the 500 pounds.
And I put that in the line so when the kids pulled, I knew how many pounds they were pulling.
We rolled it up that hill, rolled it up that slope.
It took every kid and all my block power to roll it up that hill.
They could do it.
They could do it, just could do it.
They learned it, they learned an awful lot and she said I was sick and one of the boys sent me a get well card.
I've talked to different classes on rocks and minerals and things like that.
Yeah, in my petroleum engineering courses, geology was a very strong subject.
In the early days of petroleum engineering, we did
practically all of our geology on the surface, geology.
So geology had to play an important part and of course it would not be complete without of course the mineralogy.
So all the rest of my lifetime I've been gathering, collecting minerals and rocks and so on.
Since I've retired I've got together the equipment for cutting and polishing and shaping and stuff of that sort.
So that's the other thing that I do with it.
You still collect?
Oh yeah, collect all the time.
You go out?
Yeah, rock trips, I really, that's the real fun of it.
We can get more people out on a rock trip than any place else, any other.
Meetings, that's something else, but rock trips, that's something else.
Could you tell me some of the people that are involved with your community council, some of the people that are doing the work, so we might have a record of it?
Well, the retiring president was H. Hugh Island.
He's head of the, what's now the Twin City Mission.
He was, but the presidents have been, the first president was Bill Vance, who's now county judge, and then... How many people are on this council?
Oh, there's about 12 or 15 in the board of directors.
Are they appointed?
Yeah, they're appointed.
They're elected, rather, by the membership.
The membership consists of the various organizations and the personnel of the various organizations and interested citizens.
And we have a membership schedule of dues and so on, and the membership elects the directors, and the directors elect the officers.
and the president was one of the leading people, one of the real starters, and the man that would be a real candidate for getting a lot of A&M history, because he's a guy that starts things.
His name is H.G.
Kanagy, and of course everybody calls him Andy because they were the famous Andy Kanagy, although he spells it differently.
He spells it with a K. But Andy was the one who started an organization of social services, and it fell through, and that's what gave me the clue that it had to have some activity.
So when we started the Braddock County Community Council, I said we've got to have some way to hold it together and some activity
And that's the way it turned out because there was a few years there we had presidents that were absolutely uninterested in what we were doing.
And the only thing that held it together was our activity, the information for a while.
But Andy was a starter.
Andy started action with Earl Rudder in connection with the A&M Retirees Club.
He wrote the first letters and had the first communication with Earl Rudder.

and Andy was one of the three starters in the community council, and he's one of these fellows that likes to start things and turn them over, and I like to think that Andy started the community council, but I kept it going, but then there was Bill Oxley, a preacher up here at the St. Thomas,

Harold Wells, who was a preacher at the First Presbyterian Church, those were the presidents, and now we have another preacher, Frank Dietz, he's the Faith United Church of Christ down there on South College.
But Felice Klein,
a very able woman who had a counseling service in the Berisco building for a number of years.
Now she's down at the Central Grimes Valley Mental Health.
She was a very strong worker in the community council.
Mrs. Topaz Hughes, Mrs. W. Frank Hughes,
She's a very compassionate woman and she is actually what equivalent the almoner for the First Baptist Church downtown.
She has a budget of $500 or so and if she overruns that budget, they still come up with additional money for her to use to help people out.
Now she comes to my office every Tuesday and she for 20 years now, she's been running a clothes closet
She has some money.
A kid, a teacher finds a child coming to school improperly dressed.
She writes a note to the principal, and the principal passes it on to Mrs. Hughes, and Mrs. Hughes calls the kid in and fits him up.
At the beginning of the year, he has three pairs of new jeans.
He has three sets of shirts and shorts, and he has a couple of outside shirts.
He can start the school properly dressed, and people don't.

can't tell him from somebody out here on the know because he's just as well dressed as they are and she has, this is new stuff, she also has an awful lot of used material for the children and even for some of the mothers and for 20 years now she's been handling this old clothing and the principal will say such and such kid needs clothing and
She said, go send an auto when in the afternoon at 2 o'clock, and she measures his feet and fits him up with sneakers and socks and whatever he needs, sends him home with a big bundle of clothes.
If someone comes in to you and they need to have the gas turned on and they can't pay the fee, and then you have Mrs. Hughes.
Mrs. Hughes will pay for it out of her cash allowance.
So she was the first secretary of Bradley County Community Council.
She was a woman of great compassion and she knows everybody.
She's taken a mother and two little children that were abandoned into her home or another place she found a... That's another woman.
It was one woman that she found a place you got special rates in the...

motel oh yeah we do that regularly we twist on you must be really quite a kind man by now yeah I don't take anything at face value he even got an ambulance to go and get a deathly sick man and bring him around to the doctor's back door so the doctor could get out and listen and
assigned so he could get to an institution and be taken care of.
His old fellow was bedridden and his wife was as old as he was and she wouldn't take care of him and the doctor wouldn't go 13 miles out in the country to see him for nothing.
He could make $50 while he was going out in the country, you know.
So I said, well, will you see him if I bring him in?
He said, yeah.
So I'd get the ambulance to go out and get him and bring him to the space behind the doctor's office, you know.
He takes one look at him and he certifies it.
He should be institutionalized and the welfare takes over and institutionalize them.
But he went to the hospital and he died in about a month.
There was one family that she called up and needed groceries and it was a Saturday and all the welfare people

take Saturday off of course and so it was up to Bob and I went along with him to deliver the grocery and Mr. Island had given him a box that he could hardly manage to get up onto the porch he came out and he said that was just a case of real want and it was the man was lying there and he's

little red spots on his cheeks and he had a can to spit into and I asked him whether he had any fever and he said a little and I said it's coming up in the afternoon before the evening yeah I said just cough much he said yeah got any medicine he said well I have one aspirin but I'm saving it and I said there's TB if I ever saw it so I alerted the TB and and they were real good about it I said you bring them in
you take him to the doctor and we'll pay for it.
So I took him to the doctor and he got x-rays and he didn't bother writing a report.
He called up and he said, this man's got it.
You better start taking care of him.
From there on, they were real good.
They took care of everything.
Got him the clothing.
They got him a lot of clothing and then they went through the family and the whole family got moved out to Temple.
They all had... Over east of here.
I've had a whole family in a TB sanitarium for a little bit.
But those are things that happen.
There is need.
There's a real satisfaction about it too.
There is a great deal of need and there is a need for some place where people can come and have somebody try to do something about it.
A woman in this morning, she has kidney trouble.
occasional complete kidney blockage.
She has to go to John Seeley Hospital in Galveston.
We sent her down last week and they gave her some medicine, sent her home and said come back on the 3rd of July.
So we get a charity rate from the bus company and I got the Salvation Army to buy her her bus ticket
There's a round trip ticket for $11.10 galveston.
So I arranged that.
That's the only thing I did this morning is arrange that.
Of course I am working on our number four directory now and then the- Well isn't she the one you usually made long-distance calls to the hospital so she could get in the last time she went?
Well that was a couple months ago.

A little over a month ago that she had a kidney stoppage and I called Galveston from the house here on Saturday afternoon and somebody furnished her transportation and she got that right down there and they took her in but then they turned her loose again.
Looks like she's gonna have to have an operation.
They've been fighting it off.
I guess that's, that tells the story.
We did a lot of traveling and we like, each year we like to do a little traveling.
We were, two years ago we went down through Africa, went up through Africa rather, and last year we were in Hawaii for a couple of weeks.
We just like to haul off and go, but in the meantime we
look after these things are of interest to us.
They have three sons and eleven grandchildren.
The oldest is a mechanical engineer or industrial engineer with a command company.
They've started out making helicopters.
They don't make many of them.
They make parts for

a lot of aviation parts, subcontracts, aviation parts, and then our middle son is an electrical engineer, and he works at Bell in Buffalo, and our third son is a petroleum engineer, and you'll hold it against me, but he graduated from the University of Texas.
That was in 1950 though before I came down here, but he's with the Imperial Oil Company in Alberta in Canada.
Did he ever give you a hard time about coming here?
No, he's, once in a while he says, why didn't we ever come to, because we tried to do a pretty good job of investigating all of the petroleum schools.
It was because of Dr. Fancher.
The same Dr. Fancher that I mentioned.
He was over there and Tori and the rest of them.
I thought that that was about as good a school as it was at the time but I'm convinced now that A&M is a better petroleum school.
Well, thank you.
